The article reflects on the tragic mass shooting that took place five years ago at the Route 91 Harvest Festival in Las Vegas, where a lone gunman fired over 1,000 bullets into the crowd, resulting in 60 deaths and numerous injuries. It highlights the unity and resilience shown by the people of Nevada in the aftermath of the shooting, with concertgoers risking their lives to save others and the community coming together to support the victims. The article mentions the actions taken by the current administration to address gun violence, such as executive orders and the confirmation of a permanent head for the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives. It also mentions the signing of the Bipartisan Safer Communities Act, the first significant gun violence reduction legislation in nearly 30 years. The article calls for further action, including the banning of assault weapons and high-capacity magazines, to prevent future tragedies. The author expresses condolences to those who lost loved ones and urges turning grief into action.